{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626783","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626783"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:41:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:41:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17096"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17096","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17096"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.68,0.04,0.12,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9786"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77310"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9786","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9786"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17096"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62817"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5097"},{"type":"tags","id":"5099"},{"type":"tags","id":"5102"},{"type":"tags","id":"10770"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22964"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23184"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77310","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77310"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDipeptidyl peptidase-4 (DPP-4) inhibitors are a class of oral medications used in the treatment of type 2 diabetes mellitus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of DPP-4 inhibitors?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blocks glucose absorption in the intestine","Prevents enzymatic breakdown of GLP-1 and GIP","Directly stimulates insulin release from pancreatic beta cells","Increases insulin sensitivity in peripheral tissues","Inhibits hepatic glucose production"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDPP-4 inhibitors work by \u003Cstrong\u003Epreventing the enzymatic breakdown of GLP-1\u003C/strong\u003E (glucagon-like peptide-1) and \u003Cstrong\u003EGIP (glucose-dependent insulinotropic polypeptide)\u003C/strong\u003E, both incretin hormones. This results in increased levels and prolonged action of incretins, which enhances glucose-dependent insulin secretion and supresses glucagon release. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking glucose absorption in the intestine\u003C/strong\u003E represents the mechanism of alpha-glucosidase inhibitors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirectly stimulating insulin release from pancreatic beta cells\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as DPP-4 inhibitors work indirectly through GLP-1.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing insulin sensitivity in peripheral tissues\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of thiazolidinediones.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibiting hepatic glucose production\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily the mechanism of metformin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dipeptidyl peptidase-4 (DPP-4) inhibitors prevent the breakdown of incretin hormones including glucagon-like peptide-1 (GLP-1), increasing its availability.","GLP-1 stimulates insulin secretion and suppresses glucagon release in a glucose-dependent manner.","DPP-4 inhibitors are oral medications used in type 2 diabetes management that work through the incretin pathway."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62817"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17096"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62817","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62817"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T15:54:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T15:55:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9786"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77310"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":nu